---
import Primer from '../../layouts/Primer.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';
---
<Primer
  title="What an MLIP Keeps — and Can't"
  eyebrow="A Primer on Matter Models · Chapter Six"
  deck="A DFT calculation knows a whole electronic world. The potential carries forward one slice of it. This chapter traces the edge of that slice."
  running="Ch. 6 — What an MLIP Keeps"
  prev={{ href: url('/primer/at-inference-time'), label: 'At Inference Time' }}
>
  <p class="lead">
    A DFT calculation does not merely emit an energy. To get the energy it has to solve for the
    electrons, and in solving for them it computes an entire electronic structure: where the charge
    sits, what energies the electrons are allowed to have, how the whole system would respond to a
    push or a field. The training set saw all of that. The potential was shown only a sliver. The
    question for this chapter is which parts of the electronic world survive the trip into a fitted
    function. One test decides it: can the property be written in terms of total energies — as a
    derivative of one, or a difference between two? If it can, a potential can reach it. If it
    cannot, no potential can.
  </p>

  <p>
    One converged DFT run at a fixed geometry produces raw material for all three tiers of this
    ledger at once:
  </p>

  <figure class="fig fig--ledger">
    <div class="ledger">
      <div class="ledger-head">The output of one DFT calculation</div>

      <div class="tier t1">
        <div class="tier-tag">Tier 1 — kept by every potential</div>
        <p class="tier-items">total energy · forces on each atom · stress on the cell</p>
        <p class="tier-note">…and everything that follows from them: phonons, elastic constants, and — by thermal averaging — free energies and thermal expansion.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="tier t2">
        <div class="tier-tag">Tier 2 — reachable if you ask for it in the data</div>
        <p class="tier-items">electron affinity · ionization potential · redox potential · the fundamental gap</p>
        <p class="tier-note">These are <em>energy differences between charge or spin states</em> — energies again, of different states of the same nuclei.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="tier t3">
        <div class="tier-tag">Tier 3 — out of reach for an energy model</div>
        <p class="tier-items">k-resolved band dispersion · optical absorption &amp; excitons · the dielectric function · magnetic response · conductivity</p>
        <p class="tier-note">These are <em>spectral</em> facts about the electrons at fixed nuclei, not scalars over nuclear positions.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 1</span>One calculation feeds all three tiers. A standard potential trains on the top band only. The lower two are the subject of the rest of this chapter.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 1</span>Tier 1 — the energy and its shadow</h2>

  <p>
    A conventional potential is trained to reproduce three numbers: the energy, the forces, and
    usually the stress. That is the whole target. Yet it can report far more than three numbers,
    because most of what you might want from a material is a <em>derivative</em> of the energy with
    respect to where the atoms are or how the box is shaped.
  </p>

  <p>
    Forces are the first derivative with respect to position — Chapter 1 wrote this as
    <em>F</em> = −∇<em>E</em>, the force is the downhill slope of the energy. The curvature of a
    valley, the second derivative, gives the <strong>phonons</strong>, the frequencies at which the
    lattice vibrates; from those follow vibrational entropy and heat capacity.
    Squeeze the cell and watch the energy push back: that response is the stress, and how the stress
    grows with the squeeze is the elastic constants. Hold the surface at a temperature and sample it,
    and the free energy falls out. Every one of these is a slope, or a curvature, or an accumulation
    over the same scalar function <em>E</em>(<em>R</em>) — the energy <em>E</em> as a function of all
    the nuclear coordinates <em>R</em>. If a property is some derivative of <em>E</em>(<em>R</em>), an
    energy model has, in principle, already captured it.
  </p>

  <p>
    One asterisk carries over from Chapter 1. The potential is an emulator of its training method,
    not of nature. Train on a particular DFT functional and you inherit that functional's systematic
    errors exactly. A potential can be a flawless mimic of a reference that is itself wrong. So
    "Tier 1" means "as good as the DFT you fed it," and never "as good as the experiment."
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 2</span>Tier 2 — electronic properties hiding inside energy differences</h2>

  <p>
    The same nuclei can hold electrons in more than one way. Remove one electron and the molecule is
    a cation; add one, an anion; flip a spin, and it sits in a different spin state. Each of these is
    a complete system with its own total energy over the same nuclear positions. A whole class of
    properties filed under "electronic" are nothing more than <strong>differences between those
    total energies</strong> — and total energies are exactly what an energy model traffics in.
  </p>

  <p>
    Take the <strong>electron affinity</strong>: the energy released when a neutral molecule grabs
    one more electron. It is the energy of the neutral molecule minus the energy of the same molecule
    carrying an extra electron — the anion. The <strong>ionization potential</strong> is the mirror
    image: cation minus neutral, the energy to remove an electron. The redox potential works the
    same way, by a <strong>two-calculation subtraction</strong> — run the calculation twice, once
    per charge state, and subtract (the method goes by the name ΔSCF) — and the fundamental gap is
    one step more, the ionization potential minus the electron affinity, three charge states in
    all. Each is arithmetic on the total energies of differently-charged or
    differently-spin-polarized versions of the <em>same nuclei</em>. None of them asks you to look
    inside a wavefunction.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <div class="fig-frame">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 250" role="img" aria-label="Three horizontal energy levels for the same molecule: the cation highest, the neutral in the middle, the anion lowest. The ionization potential is the gap from neutral up to cation; the electron affinity is the gap from anion up to neutral.">
        <text x="360" y="30" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">same nuclei, three charge states</text>

        <!-- cation (highest energy) -->
        <line x1="170" y1="70" x2="430" y2="70" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="2" />
        <text x="150" y="74" text-anchor="end" class="svg-serif-it">cation</text>
        <text x="440" y="74" class="svg-small">remove an electron</text>

        <!-- neutral (middle) -->
        <line x1="170" y1="140" x2="430" y2="140" stroke="var(--oxblood)" stroke-width="2.4" />
        <text x="150" y="144" text-anchor="end" class="svg-serif-it">neutral</text>

        <!-- anion (lowest) -->
        <line x1="170" y1="200" x2="430" y2="200" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="2" />
        <text x="150" y="204" text-anchor="end" class="svg-serif-it">anion</text>
        <text x="440" y="204" class="svg-small">add an electron</text>

        <!-- IP gap: neutral up to cation -->
        <line x1="300" y1="140" x2="300" y2="70" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.1" marker-start="url(#ch5gapA)" marker-end="url(#ch5gapA)" />
        <text x="312" y="108" class="svg-serif" style="font-size:14px;">IP = E(cation) − E(neutral)</text>

        <!-- EA gap: anion up to neutral -->
        <line x1="300" y1="200" x2="300" y2="140" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.1" marker-start="url(#ch5gapA)" marker-end="url(#ch5gapA)" />
        <text x="312" y="174" class="svg-serif" style="font-size:14px;">EA = E(neutral) − E(anion)</text>

        <defs>
          <marker id="ch5gapA" markerWidth="9" markerHeight="9" refX="4.5" refY="4.5" orient="auto">
            <path d="M0 4.5 L9 0 L9 9 z" fill="var(--ink)" />
          </marker>
        </defs>
      </svg>
    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 2</span>The same molecule at three charge states. The gap upward to the cation is the ionization potential; the gap downward to the anion is the electron affinity. Both are subtractions of total energies.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Two things make this reachable for an energy model. First, the data has to contain those states:
    the reference set must include the charged and spin-varied versions of each molecule, computed
    with DFT. Second, the model has to be <em>told</em> which state it is looking at. A dataset like
    <strong>OMol25</strong> does both. It carries a charge and a spin multiplicity for every
    structure, it spans many charge and spin states, and those two numbers — total charge and spin
    multiplicity — are handed to the model as global inputs alongside the geometry. The model is not
    blind to charge. It knows the molecule in front of it is the anion rather than the neutral,
    because you said so.
  </p>

  <aside class="sidenote">
    <span class="sn-label">What the model still does not have</span>
    These networks predict energy and forces. They do not contain explicit long-range electrostatics
    or a charge-equilibration step — there is no machinery inside that solves where charge flows
    across the molecule. They reach the redox and affinity numbers by having learned the energies of
    the right states, not by modeling the electrostatic physics that produces them.
  </aside>

  <p>
    In an independent benchmark against measured
    reduction potentials and electron affinities — experimental numbers, not DFT — models trained
    on OMol25 compete with low-cost quantum chemistry. The result is not uniform. On
    <strong>organometallic systems</strong> — metal centers wrapped in organic ligands, the
    workhorses of catalysis — the best UMA variants land within about 0.26 volts on reduction
    potentials and 0.17 electron-volts on electron affinities, smaller errors than the usual
    semiempirical and cheap-DFT shortcuts manage. On <strong>main-group species</strong> — ordinary
    light-element molecules — the learned models are merely on par with those shortcuts, and some
    miss reduction potentials by more than a volt. The split is the mirror image of the traditional
    methods', which have always been strongest on the main group and weakest on metals.
  </p>

  <p>
    None of it would be reachable without the right reference data. OMol25 was computed at the
    ωB97M-V/def2-TZVPD level — a range-separated hybrid functional paired with a basis set that
    includes <em>diffuse</em> functions, the loosely-bound tails an electron needs when it is barely
    held by a molecule. Those diffuse tails are exactly what an anion has and a neutral does not, so
    they matter precisely for electron affinities. The learned model's ceiling is whatever its
    reference can do; you pay for Tier 2 in reference calculations, not in a new kind of
    network.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 3</span>Tier 3 — where an energy model cannot follow</h2>

  <p>
    Now the wall. Some properties are not energy differences between states. They are properties of
    the electronic <em>spectrum</em> at fixed nuclei: the band structure resolved by momentum, the
    optical absorption with its excitonic peaks, the dielectric function, magnetic response,
    conductivity. The reason no energy model reaches these is architectural.
  </p>

  <p>
    A potential's entire output is one scalar, <em>E</em>(<em>R</em>) — the energy as a function of
    where the nuclei sit. Forces, phonons, elastic constants, free energies are all derivatives of
    that scalar with respect to nuclear position. A spectrum is not. A spectrum is a fact about the
    <strong>electronic Hamiltonian</strong> — the operator that governs the electrons — at a
    <em>fixed</em> geometry. Diagonalize that operator and you get the energies an electron is
    allowed to have: the band structure. The rest of Tier 3 — absorption, the dielectric function,
    conductivity — is response built on those allowed states: how the electrons answer light or a
    field. Differentiating <em>E</em>(<em>R</em>) asks how the ground-state
    energy changes as you move atoms. The spectrum asks something the ground-state energy never
    recorded: what the electrons could do without moving an atom at all. No amount of differentiating
    <em>E</em>(<em>R</em>) produces a spectrum. The information was never in the object being
    differentiated.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <div class="fig-frame">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 286" role="img" aria-label="Two model output spaces side by side. An energy model outputs a scalar E(R), which you differentiate to get forces and phonons. A Hamiltonian model outputs an operator, which you diagonalize to get spectra. A dashed line divides them.">
        <line x1="360" y1="28" x2="360" y2="262" stroke="var(--rule)" stroke-width="0.75" stroke-dasharray="3 4" />

        <!-- LEFT: energy model -->
        <text x="180" y="40" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">an energy model</text>
        <rect x="110" y="58" width="140" height="44" fill="none" stroke="var(--oxblood)" stroke-width="1.6" />
        <text x="180" y="85" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif" style="font-size:15px;">E(R) — a scalar</text>
        <line x1="180" y1="102" x2="180" y2="150" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.2" marker-end="url(#ch5fork)" />
        <text x="190" y="130" class="svg-small">differentiate</text>
        <text x="180" y="172" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif-it">forces · stress</text>
        <text x="180" y="192" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif-it">phonons · elastic constants</text>
        <text x="180" y="212" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif-it">free energies</text>
        <text x="180" y="246" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">(Tiers 1 &amp; 2 live here)</text>

        <!-- RIGHT: hamiltonian model -->
        <text x="540" y="40" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">a Hamiltonian model</text>
        <rect x="470" y="58" width="140" height="44" fill="none" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.6" />
        <text x="540" y="85" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif" style="font-size:15px;">Ĥ(R) — an operator</text>
        <line x1="540" y1="102" x2="540" y2="150" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.2" marker-end="url(#ch5fork)" />
        <text x="550" y="130" class="svg-small">diagonalize</text>
        <text x="540" y="172" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif-it">band structure · density of states</text>
        <text x="540" y="192" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">…and, with response theory on top:</text>
        <text x="540" y="212" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif-it">absorption · dielectric · conductivity</text>
        <text x="540" y="246" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">(Tier 3 lives here)</text>

        <defs>
          <marker id="ch5fork" markerWidth="9" markerHeight="9" refX="7" refY="4.5" orient="auto">
            <path d="M0 0 L9 4.5 L0 9 z" fill="var(--ink)" />
          </marker>
        </defs>
      </svg>
    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 3</span>The fork is in the output. An energy model emits a scalar you differentiate. A Tier-3 model emits an electronic object you diagonalize. These are different machines, not a better-trained and a worse-trained version of one machine.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    The far side of the fork has names. A <strong>DeepH</strong>-style network predicts the DFT
    Hamiltonian itself — the operator, not the energy. You take its predicted operator, diagonalize
    it, and read off the band structure and density of states directly. Further still,
    neural-network wavefunctions such as <strong>FermiNet</strong> and <strong>PauliNet</strong> learn
    the many-electron wavefunction directly and variationally. These last two are not trained against
    DFT labels at all; they are <em>ab initio</em>, optimized against the Schrödinger equation itself.
    In their base form they solve for the ground state, but they stand on the right side of the fork:
    the wavefunction is the object the spectrum lives in, and excited-state extensions of the same
    machinery read it out — something no amount of energy fitting could do.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 4</span>Why the energy side raced ahead</h2>

  <p>
    If Tier 3 is a matter of predicting a different object, why is nearly every model in this almanac
    an energy model? The answer is the <strong>labels</strong>, not the architecture.
  </p>

  <p>
    Energies and forces are an almost-free by-product of any DFT run. You were going to converge the
    calculation anyway, and they fall out of it. That made it cheap to assemble datasets of millions
    of configurations, and energy models feasted on them. Spectral ground truth is the opposite. A
    faithful band structure wants a GW calculation — a many-body method that fixes the
    electron-level energies plain DFT gets systematically wrong, at ten to a hundred times the cost. Optical absorption
    with excitons wants the Bethe-Salpeter equation (BSE) on top of GW, costlier still, and on solids
    these are punishing. There is no materials-scale dataset of band structures
    because no one can afford to compute one. The energy side raced ahead because its ground truth was
    affordable. The bottleneck for Tier 3 is the reference data, not the model.
  </p>

  <p>
    The wall does not move with scale. UMA, trained on half a billion arrangements, is still an
    energy, force, and stress model; it lives on the Tier-1 and Tier-2 side and does not cross into
    spectra. Pushing an energy model onto charge- and spin-difference properties (Tier 2) and
    building a Hamiltonian predictor (Tier 3) are two separate moves. Stacking more energy data
    sharpens the first and never starts the second.
  </p>

  <p>
    That is the whole trade. A potential keeps the energy and everything the energy can shadow, and
    gives up the rest of the electronic world in exchange for a million-fold speedup. Everything
    cataloged in this almanac lives inside that slice — and now you know exactly where its edges
    are.
  </p>

